A malignant brain tumor is a cancerous growth that may affect brain function, leading to various neurological symptoms depending on its location and size. These symptoms can include speech difficulties, weakness or paralysis on one side of the body, seizures, headaches, and changes in personality or behavior. Diagnosis typically involves imaging tests like MRI or CT scans.

On the other hand, a transient ischemic attack is caused by a temporary disruption of blood flow to a part of the brain. It can produce stroke-like symptoms, including sudden trouble speaking, weakness or numbness on one side of the body, and impaired movement. TIAs typically last for a short time, often less than an hour, and their effects are usually temporary. However, TIAs are often considered warning signs of an increased risk for a future stroke, thus requiring immediate medical attention.

It's vital not to self-diagnose and see a doctor promptly if you're experiencing these symptoms. They can properly evaluate your situation, conduct the necessary tests, and determine the cause of your symptoms.
